x4freetext: K-400 Neutron Generator at the
Institute of Nuclear Physics and Chemistry, China
Academy of Engineering Physics (CAEP) and lasted
6-10 h with a yield about 3-4 x 10**10 n/s.
The natural osmium powder of 99.9% purity was made
into circular thin samples with a diameter of 20mm
and the thickness of 3-5mm, which were sandwiched
between two disks of thin Nb of the same diameter.
The purity of the Nb metal was better than 99.99%.
well-calibrated GEM-60P coaxial HPGe detector
(crystal diameter: 70.1mm, crystal length: 72.3mm)
(ORTEC, made in USA) with a relative efficiency of
approx.68% and an energy resolution of approx.
1.69keV FWHM at 1.33 MeV. The uncertainty in the
absolute efficiency curve at 2.8cm was estimated to be
approx. 2%, and the uncertainty of the activity of the
standard source was approx. 1%.
Neutrons around the energy of 14 MeV were
produced by the T(d,n)4He reaction with an
effective deuteron beam of 134 keV and a beam
current of 230 mu-A.
The solid tritium-titanium (T-Ti) target used in the
generator was about 2.18 mg/cm2 thick.
Uncertainty in the incident energy
Several sources of uncertainties were taken
into account to determine the uncertainties of our
cross-section values, such as:
* statistical uncertainties (0.3-4.1%),
* uncertainties of the cross section for the reference
reaction 93Nb(n,2n)92mNb (1-2%)
uncertainties in sample weights
uncertainties in the calibration of HPGe
detector
